WEBVTT

01:10.300 --> 01:13.800
[ Woman ] I'm pretty hungry.
I hope we catch some fish soon.
[ Child ] Me too.

01:13.870 --> 01:16.510
Okay, help me wind.
Wind back?

01:16.580 --> 01:20.150
Can we turn this one?
Slowly.

01:20.210 --> 01:22.510
Slowly, slowly,
slowly, slowly.

01:22.580 --> 01:25.550
I am doing it slowly.
Okay, you got it.

01:25.620 --> 01:27.530
Oh, Matty, look!

01:27.590 --> 01:30.030
You see that?
See that big boat out there?
Mm-hmm.

01:30.090 --> 01:35.890
She is the prettiest boat
on Whidbey Island.
That's the Morning Star.

01:35.960 --> 01:38.990
Someday when you're
big enough, I'm gonna
teach you how to sail.

01:39.070 --> 01:41.970
It's the best thing
there is, sailing.
Better than fishing?

01:42.040 --> 01:45.310
Yup.
But you know what, kiddo?

01:45.370 --> 01:47.370
I don't think
I want you to grow up.

01:47.440 --> 01:50.410
Why?
What if you grow up
and marry some beautiful girl?

01:50.480 --> 01:54.520
Who's gonna go sailing
with me then?
Dad.

01:54.580 --> 01:56.380
Not a chance.

01:56.450 --> 01:58.450
** [ Light Jazz ]
[ Chattering ]

02:01.790 --> 02:03.630
Thank you so much.

02:12.300 --> 02:15.360
Nick.
Uh, we need to talk.

02:15.440 --> 02:17.810
Always happy to talk
to you, Rudy.

02:17.870 --> 02:21.600
Hey, Warren.
Did you get that notice
from First Seattle today?

02:21.680 --> 02:23.980
Yeah. Yeah, as a matter
of fact, I did.
[ Chuckles ]

02:24.040 --> 02:26.380
Good.
Then you know.

02:26.450 --> 02:30.390
We've got
a real problem.
First Seattle is not a problem.

02:30.450 --> 02:33.020
These martinis are a problem.
Do you mind?

02:33.090 --> 02:36.330
Not at all.
Where were we?
All right, First Seattle.

02:37.430 --> 02:40.430
- Mommy?
- Hey, kiddo.

02:40.490 --> 02:43.990
How's it going?
Hand off.

02:44.060 --> 02:46.200
[ Both Grunting ]

02:46.270 --> 02:48.670
Oh, you sack
of potatoes.
Ay-yi-yi.

02:48.740 --> 02:51.110
Have you been carrying him
around the whole party?
Yeah.

02:51.170 --> 02:53.170
We're never gonna
marry you off, Angie.

02:53.240 --> 02:57.970
Mm, yes. Picasso.

02:58.050 --> 03:00.250
Blue Period.

03:00.310 --> 03:03.350
The artist's name
is Kandinsky.

03:03.420 --> 03:05.490
Wassily Kandinsky.

03:05.550 --> 03:09.950
He was German,
of Russian extraction,
1866 to 1944.

03:10.020 --> 03:12.760
And by the way,
Picasso's Blue Period
was figurative,

03:12.830 --> 03:14.900
and ended in 1904.

03:14.960 --> 03:19.360
And these watercolors
are abstract, done in 1911.

03:23.240 --> 03:26.450
[ Scoffs ]
Picasso.

03:28.880 --> 03:31.480
Everyone pipe down.
I'm about to give a speech.

03:31.550 --> 03:34.620
Thank you for coming.
I always say the sign
of a good party...

03:34.680 --> 03:36.910
is when I'm having a better time
than anyone else, but...

03:36.980 --> 03:39.350
now is the time when you're
expected to ante up...

03:39.420 --> 03:41.650
for drinking all my liquor,
and eating all my food,

03:41.720 --> 03:46.290
and spilling tomato sauce
on my couch, Bobby Long.

03:46.360 --> 03:50.090
- [ Crowd ] Ooh-- [ Laughs ]
- What, you didn't think
I saw you?

03:50.160 --> 03:53.030
Oh, he's insufferable.
I know it.

03:53.100 --> 03:55.960
Now, we are here to raise
a vast sum of money
for the Small Frye school.

03:56.040 --> 04:00.050
So, while you are reaching
for your checkbooks,

04:00.110 --> 04:02.480
it gives me great pleasure to
introduce Mrs. Rebecca Tingley,

04:02.540 --> 04:04.770
our totally ravishing...

04:04.850 --> 04:07.950
and completely adorable
Headmistress.

04:08.020 --> 04:11.360
[ Clapping, Whistling ]

04:11.420 --> 04:13.590
Mr. Parsons, thank you.
[ Chuckles ]

04:13.650 --> 04:16.450
First of all, I'd like
to start by introducing...

04:16.520 --> 04:20.720
- a few members of my staff
to you today.
- Oh, God.

04:20.790 --> 04:23.430
I give you
our dedicated teacher
and Head of Admissions,

04:23.500 --> 04:25.440
Miss Angela Green.

04:25.500 --> 04:28.440
[ Clapping ]
Yea!

04:28.500 --> 04:32.870
[ Boy Speaking,
Indistinct ]
Me!

04:41.550 --> 04:45.760
What are you
thinking about?

04:45.820 --> 04:48.830
Was I always as rude
as I am now?
[ Giggles ]

04:48.890 --> 04:51.100
Absolutely.

04:51.160 --> 04:53.370
[ Chuckles ]

05:00.270 --> 05:04.510
Hi.
Come have a seat.

05:13.810 --> 05:16.450
Angela,
do you think we ought
to break the news to her?

05:16.520 --> 05:19.690
I suppose it's better
she hears it from us
than from someone else.

05:19.750 --> 05:22.180
She's not gonna be
happy about it.

05:22.260 --> 05:24.460
What's up, guys?

05:25.390 --> 05:27.320
Close your eyes.

05:27.400 --> 05:30.370
Close 'em.

05:30.430 --> 05:34.330
Okay, now,
stand up.

05:34.400 --> 05:37.070
Keep 'em closed.

05:37.140 --> 05:40.550
** [ Humming ]

05:44.280 --> 05:46.420
Now, Libby,
what is your favorite thing?

05:46.480 --> 05:48.980
Me?
Not even close.

05:50.950 --> 05:53.450
All right, open.

05:55.990 --> 05:58.030
I heard Sean Gittman
was thinking of selling.

05:58.090 --> 05:59.960
I made him an offer,

06:00.030 --> 06:02.100
and he agreed to let us
take her out for the weekend.

06:02.160 --> 06:04.490
And if you like it,
it's yours.

06:04.570 --> 06:07.170
If I like it?
[ Chuckles ]
Mm-hmm.

06:07.230 --> 06:09.670
Honey,
we can't afford that.

06:09.740 --> 06:12.040
When have I ever let that
get in my way? Come on.

06:12.110 --> 06:14.410
[ Laughs ]
Huh?

06:14.480 --> 06:18.520
- What about Matty?
- I'll take care of him.
We'll have a great time.

06:20.150 --> 06:22.720
You hate to sail.

06:22.780 --> 06:24.880
I can learn.

06:27.220 --> 06:29.720
[ Chuckles ]
Huh?

06:53.850 --> 06:57.420
Generally, wine like this
needs time to breathe,

06:57.490 --> 07:00.690
but I don't know,
I don't think we should...

07:00.750 --> 07:02.620
wait.

07:03.620 --> 07:05.650
I don't see land.

07:08.530 --> 07:11.440
So where is it?

07:11.500 --> 07:13.840
Alaska's over that way,
Japan is straight ahead,

07:13.900 --> 07:16.630
and Australia's
somewhere to the left.

07:16.700 --> 07:18.730
Where would
you like to go?

07:18.810 --> 07:20.580
Bed.

07:20.640 --> 07:23.640
That can be arranged.

07:31.320 --> 07:35.060
[ Sighing, Gasping ]

07:35.120 --> 07:37.650
[ Soft Moaning ]

07:41.390 --> 07:43.630
[ Both Giggling ]

08:08.520 --> 08:11.420
We should do this
more often.

08:11.490 --> 08:14.390
What do you mean?
Buy expensive sailboats?

08:14.460 --> 08:17.560
[ Chuckles ]
If this is what happens,
I'll buy another one tomorrow.

08:17.630 --> 08:22.200
[ Chuckles ]
No, go away,
just the two of us,

08:22.270 --> 08:24.580
with nobody else around.

08:29.110 --> 08:31.120
I'll drink to that.

08:34.280 --> 08:37.410
[ Banging, Squeaking ]

08:37.480 --> 08:39.510
[ Banging Continues ]

08:41.560 --> 08:43.660
Nick?

08:48.030 --> 08:50.740
Nick?

08:52.670 --> 08:55.810
Oh, my God.
Nick?

08:59.270 --> 09:01.140
[ Louder ]
Nick?

09:07.720 --> 09:10.160
[ Whimpering ]

09:13.750 --> 09:16.790
Nick?
Ni--

09:16.860 --> 09:20.570
Oh, my God.
[ Whimpering ]

09:35.810 --> 09:37.850
Nick?
[ Whimpering ]

09:40.410 --> 09:44.610
[ Gasping, Moaning ]

09:46.350 --> 09:50.220
Nick!
[ Screaming ]
Nick!

09:52.160 --> 09:55.170
Nick!
[ Sobbing ]
Oh, my God.

09:56.730 --> 10:00.830
Oh, my God.
Oh, my God.

10:00.900 --> 10:02.930
[ Horn Blaring ]
Nick?

10:04.670 --> 10:07.400
[ Man On P.A. ]
Morning Star, this is
the Coast Guard.

10:07.470 --> 10:10.810
Put the knife down,
ma'am, and step away.

10:10.880 --> 10:13.620
I-I don't--
I don't know--

10:13.680 --> 10:17.480
I don't know...
where my husband is!

10:17.550 --> 10:20.180
[ Female Reporter ]
...an around-the-clock search
for local businessman...

10:20.250 --> 10:23.790
Nick Parsons,
who disappeared in these waters
off Whidbey Island.

10:31.600 --> 10:34.140
[ Man ]
All right, tie it off.

10:36.270 --> 10:39.680
- Hey, Cutter.
- Hey, Tom.
What have you got for me?

10:41.740 --> 10:44.110
[ Voices Indistinct,
Drowned Out By Boat Motors ]

10:53.350 --> 10:56.350
Anything?
No.

10:56.420 --> 10:59.120
Cutter, please don't let them
give up. He's very strong.

10:59.190 --> 11:02.660
Libby.
L-Libby.
He's a very strong man.

11:05.300 --> 11:09.810
[ Gasping ]
The raft and life preservers
are all on board.

11:09.870 --> 11:14.440
These guys,
they tracked the wind,
currents--

11:15.810 --> 11:20.290
Nothing.
The water temperature
overnight...

11:20.350 --> 11:22.190
was 51 degrees.

11:22.250 --> 11:25.060
That's cold.
That's really cold.
[ Gasping ]

11:26.920 --> 11:29.580
Cutter,
I can't breathe!
Just put your head down.

11:29.660 --> 11:31.760
Yeah, that's it.
Deep breaths.

11:31.830 --> 11:33.970
Big breaths.

11:36.900 --> 11:39.440
[ Sobbing ]
Shh.

12:01.920 --> 12:05.650
- [ Police Radio Chattering ]
- Mommy, look!

12:05.730 --> 12:08.270
[ Car Doors Slamming ]

12:16.100 --> 12:18.500
Hi, kiddo.

12:20.470 --> 12:22.340
Hey, Bobby.

12:24.780 --> 12:27.050
Hey, Libby.
[ Sighs ]

12:27.110 --> 12:30.080
Um, well Cutter, he, uh--

12:30.150 --> 12:32.450
He asked me to come by
and talk to you, you know.

12:32.520 --> 12:35.490
Just, um--
Not as an attorney,
just as a friend.

12:37.890 --> 12:40.690
The inquest was held
this morning, and they
reviewed all the evidence,

12:40.760 --> 12:44.930
and Nick, uh,
well, he's officially
been declared dead.

12:46.870 --> 12:50.180
Now, Libby, they, um--

12:50.240 --> 12:53.780
they've determined
it was a "wrongful death,"
and you--

12:53.840 --> 12:58.610
Oh, Jesus, you--
You're being formally
charged with his murder.

12:58.680 --> 13:00.450
[ Laughs ]
I am here to advise you.

13:00.510 --> 13:03.280
Make no statements
whatsoever to the sheriff.

13:05.620 --> 13:07.790
I'm sorry, Libby.

13:12.430 --> 13:14.770
[ Scoffing ]
Cutter!

13:14.830 --> 13:17.440
Not in front
of my kid, okay?

13:29.010 --> 13:32.250
[ Key Turning ]

13:45.430 --> 13:48.900
I'm sorry, Libby.
Uh, the judge denied us bail.

13:53.470 --> 13:55.410
[ Opening Briefcase ]

13:59.970 --> 14:02.100
Can Angie
keep looking after Matty?

14:04.240 --> 14:08.440
Good. Okay, uh--
[ Sighs ]

14:08.520 --> 14:12.390
Let's take a look at this,
see what we can do.
Bobby.

14:12.450 --> 14:14.850
Here's what
I think happened.

14:16.490 --> 14:19.200
I had some wine, okay?

14:19.260 --> 14:21.700
And I fell asleep.
It must have been the sun.

14:21.760 --> 14:26.590
And maybe Nick was trying
to cut a snagged line
or something,

14:26.670 --> 14:30.140
because the knife...

14:30.200 --> 14:32.400
from the galley
was on deck.

14:32.470 --> 14:36.670
And-And maybe the boat
pitched or something,

14:36.740 --> 14:38.640
and he cut himself.

14:38.710 --> 14:41.940
And he tried to come downstairs.
He tried to come below...

14:42.020 --> 14:44.890
to wake me up.

14:49.860 --> 14:52.460
[ Sighs ]

14:52.530 --> 14:54.630
[ Chuckles ]

14:56.860 --> 14:58.960
I quit these things
when I met Nick.

15:00.200 --> 15:03.030
It'll be all right.
I promise you.

15:04.740 --> 15:08.480
So. Why don't we take a look
at this First Guarantee Life?

15:10.180 --> 15:13.250
Now. You both bought
life insurance policies...

15:13.310 --> 15:16.380
from the company
around four months ago.

15:18.620 --> 15:22.590
- And you are the beneficiary.
- I'm his wife.

15:22.660 --> 15:25.530
- Libby, you know this policy
is worth two million?
- Nick wanted to make sure...

15:25.590 --> 15:28.460
that if anything happened
to him, we'd be okay.

15:28.530 --> 15:31.600
The jury may feel
there's a big difference
between "okay" and $2 million.

15:31.660 --> 15:33.860
They may see it
as a motive.

15:33.930 --> 15:36.530
- Is that what they're saying?
- No, no one is saying that.

15:36.600 --> 15:41.270
I don't think we have
to be concerned about--
That I killed Nick for money?

15:41.340 --> 15:45.110
[ Scoffs ]

15:45.180 --> 15:47.120
I know we had some problems,
and Nick worried,

15:47.180 --> 15:49.210
but we were okay!
Libby!

15:49.280 --> 15:52.480
Two of his investors
were suing him for embezzlement.

15:52.550 --> 15:55.020
First Seattle issued
a lien on all of his
real estate properties,

15:55.090 --> 15:57.400
your personal possessions--

15:57.460 --> 15:59.460
Now, Nick's death means
all these problems disappear...

15:59.530 --> 16:04.070
behind a corporate shield,
leaving you with $2 million.

16:07.070 --> 16:10.780
- Do you think I killed him?
- That's the first rule
of being a lawyer.

16:10.840 --> 16:12.840
What we think doesn't matter.

16:12.910 --> 16:15.250
It matters to me.

16:18.050 --> 16:21.190
No. Of course.
I don't think you killed him.

16:24.820 --> 16:27.930
[ Woman ]
Petty Officer Young,
what was the condition...

16:27.990 --> 16:31.830
of the Morning Star's
marine band radio when you had
a chance to inspect it?

16:31.890 --> 16:34.190
The handset cord
had been cut.

16:34.260 --> 16:37.030
And as you initially
approached the sailboat,

16:37.100 --> 16:39.970
what did you see?

16:40.030 --> 16:42.800
Mrs. Parsons
was holding a knife.

16:42.870 --> 16:44.710
[ Spectators Murmuring ]

16:46.170 --> 16:51.070
I show you State's exhibit...
number four.

16:51.140 --> 16:53.180
[ Nick's Voice ]
Uh, Mayday. Mayday.

16:53.250 --> 16:55.250
This is the Morning Star.

16:55.320 --> 16:57.820
[ Man ]
State your emergency,
Morning Star.

16:57.880 --> 16:59.910
I've been stabbed.

16:59.990 --> 17:03.330
I'm bleeding, uh--
Oh, Jesus.

17:03.390 --> 17:06.250
My na-- My name's
Nicholas Parsons.

17:06.330 --> 17:09.800
[ Man ]
State your position.
I don't know, man.

17:09.860 --> 17:15.100
Three miles northwest of,
uh, of Whidbey Island, I guess.

17:15.170 --> 17:18.840
Oh, God!
Oh, God!
[ Clicks ]

17:18.910 --> 17:22.150
[ Woman ] Mrs. Parsons,
you've heard the testimony
presented to this court,

17:22.210 --> 17:27.520
and your explanation is
that somebody must have
come aboard the Morning Star.

17:27.580 --> 17:33.320
- That's right.
- Well, let's consider
all the possibilities.

17:33.390 --> 17:35.790
Maybe a band of pirates.

17:35.860 --> 17:39.360
Or aliens!
Did aliens murder
your husband?

17:39.430 --> 17:42.870
[ Snaps Fingers ]
No. Aliens weren't
beneficiaries...

17:42.930 --> 17:45.370
in your husband's
life insurance policy.
Objection.

17:45.430 --> 17:47.500
Your Honor,
the prosecutor--
Overruled.

17:47.570 --> 17:50.510
- I told you what happened.
- Yes, you did.

17:50.570 --> 17:53.900
- You told us
that you were asleep.
- Yes.

17:53.970 --> 17:57.310
Maybe you were sleepwalking
when you stabbed your husband.

17:57.380 --> 18:01.090
Objection. Is Miss Halliwell
questioning the witness,
or making a closing argument?

18:01.150 --> 18:05.890
- Withdrawn.
- I didn't kill my husband!

18:05.950 --> 18:07.880
I loved my husband.
[ Sobbing ]

18:07.950 --> 18:11.420
[ Hysterical Sobbing ]

18:11.490 --> 18:16.360
Bobby, I did not
kill my husband!

18:16.430 --> 18:19.640
You have to believe me.

18:19.700 --> 18:21.810
[ Sobs Echo, Fade ]

18:34.980 --> 18:37.350
[ Bobby ]
I'm-I'm sorry, Libby.

18:39.150 --> 18:42.280
It's not your fault,
Bobby.

18:42.360 --> 18:45.830
** [ Humming ]

18:47.790 --> 18:49.860
[ Door Closes ]

18:52.630 --> 18:54.900
I want to ask you
something, Angie.

18:57.500 --> 18:59.500
I'd like you
to adopt my son.

19:01.510 --> 19:03.820
No, Lib, I can't do that.
Not to you.

19:03.880 --> 19:06.680
I've thought it through.

19:06.750 --> 19:10.690
I barely survived
my parents' house.
I'm not gonna put him there.

19:10.750 --> 19:12.980
** [ Humming ]

19:13.050 --> 19:16.680
Money won't be
a problem because
there's the $2 million...

19:16.760 --> 19:19.430
from the life insurance,
and it's going into
a trust fund in his name.

19:19.490 --> 19:23.390
- It isn't about money.
- [ Whispering ] I know.

19:23.460 --> 19:26.290
[ Matty Talking
Softly ]

19:26.370 --> 19:30.170
Matty loves you.

19:31.940 --> 19:34.580
We can't let him become
a ward of the state.

19:34.640 --> 19:37.770
[ Matty Makes
Gunfire Sounds ]

19:38.980 --> 19:41.650
** [ Humming ]

19:48.420 --> 19:50.650
[ Softly ]
Thank you.

19:52.730 --> 19:54.730
Hey, kiddo.

19:54.790 --> 19:56.860
Come see me.

19:56.930 --> 19:59.270
[ Chuckles ]

20:00.900 --> 20:03.800
You're gonna go stay
with Angie for a while.
Okay, kiddo?

20:03.870 --> 20:05.700
Okay.

20:05.770 --> 20:09.470
And you're gonna have
lots of fun,

20:09.540 --> 20:12.940
and I know you're gonna be
a good boy, right?

20:13.010 --> 20:15.180
Yes, mommy.

20:15.250 --> 20:18.360
And as soon as
all this is over,

20:18.420 --> 20:22.230
we'll be together again.

20:22.290 --> 20:24.730
That's a promise, kiddo.

20:24.790 --> 20:26.690
Okay?

20:28.090 --> 20:30.760
I love you.

20:30.830 --> 20:33.400
I love you, too.

21:09.940 --> 21:12.480
[ Siren Blaring ]

21:13.970 --> 21:15.970
[ Siren Continues ]

21:19.410 --> 21:21.680
[ Inmates Chattering ]

21:29.060 --> 21:32.430
- Who's this?
- Rich bitch
from Whidbey Island.

21:32.490 --> 21:36.890
She ain't gonna make it.
What do you think--
a year?

21:36.960 --> 21:41.100
Five cartons says
she offs herself
inside of six months.

21:41.170 --> 21:43.740
- Deal.
- Get away from me.

21:43.800 --> 21:46.370
Hey, take it easy.
We're you new best friends.

21:46.440 --> 21:49.810
Heard you did your husband.
Probably deserved it.

21:49.880 --> 21:51.880
Mine did.

21:53.550 --> 21:55.820
[ Chattering, Coughing ]

22:06.130 --> 22:07.970
[ Chattering, Laughing ]

22:09.600 --> 22:12.600
[ Overlapping Conversations ]

22:16.670 --> 22:18.940
[ Libby ]
I know what a pain it is
to get here.

22:19.010 --> 22:21.750
I taught him how
to say the ABC's.
Is that true?

22:21.810 --> 22:23.750
Sing it, Matty.
Go!
Yes.

22:23.810 --> 22:26.310
Did you learn
the alphabet, sweetie?

22:26.380 --> 22:28.350
Yeah.
Can you tell me?

22:28.420 --> 22:32.620
* A, B, C, D
E, F, G *

22:32.690 --> 22:34.590
* H, I, J, K *
[ Laughing ]

22:34.650 --> 22:36.580
* L, M, N, O, P *

22:36.660 --> 22:39.400
* Q, R, S
T, U, V *

22:39.460 --> 22:44.070
* W, X
Y and Z *

22:44.130 --> 22:48.400
* Now I know my ABC's *

22:48.470 --> 22:52.740
* Next time won't you
sing with me **

23:04.320 --> 23:07.120
[ Line Ringing ]
Give it up.
Come on.

23:07.190 --> 23:10.630
Get off the phone,
bitch. Jesus.
[ Ringing Continues ]

23:19.030 --> 23:21.500
[ Weeping ]

23:29.440 --> 23:31.770
[ Weeping Continues ]

23:46.790 --> 23:48.720
Whoa, you're low
on cigarettes.

23:48.800 --> 23:50.740
If you want to make
any friends,

23:50.800 --> 23:52.740
I advise you buy
another pack fast--

23:52.800 --> 23:54.670
on account of
your personality,

23:54.730 --> 23:56.800
It ain't the best
I've ever seen.

23:56.870 --> 24:00.010
Hear you're tryin'
to reach your friend,
the one with your boy.

24:00.070 --> 24:02.770
Yeah, I can't find 'em.
They disappeared.

24:02.840 --> 24:06.070
Oh, hon-- If you could
disappear that easy,

24:06.150 --> 24:08.220
believe you me,
I wouldn't be here
right now.

24:08.280 --> 24:10.080
[ Chuckles ]
Me either.

24:13.350 --> 24:16.650
Think.
Use your head.

24:16.720 --> 24:19.120
There's gotta be a way
to track 'em down.

24:23.600 --> 24:26.100
[ Chattering,
Laughing Continue ]

24:29.840 --> 24:31.840
Small Frye School,
front office.
Shh! Shh!

24:31.900 --> 24:33.940
Hello, this is
Angela Green calling.

24:34.010 --> 24:36.250
Angie,
it's Jennifer.
Yes, hi. How are you?

24:36.310 --> 24:38.820
Good to hear from you.
Yes, it's nice
to hear your voice.

24:38.880 --> 24:41.990
Listen, I haven't gotten
a severance check in a while,

24:42.050 --> 24:44.460
and I was hoping
I could verify with you...

24:44.520 --> 24:46.920
that you have
my correct mailing address
and phone number.

24:46.990 --> 24:50.130
Sure, I'll check.
Can you hold on a sec?
Yes, of course. Thank you.

24:50.190 --> 24:52.230
[ Chattering ]

24:53.990 --> 24:57.630
Yeah, I have it right here.
Tell me if this is right.

24:57.700 --> 25:02.140
3321 Mason Street,
San Francisco...

25:02.200 --> 25:04.330
94105.

25:04.400 --> 25:07.030
The phone number
is 415--

25:07.110 --> 25:10.550
[ Ringing ]

25:10.610 --> 25:12.510
[ Beeps ]
Hello?

25:12.580 --> 25:16.950
Angie? Angie.
Libby? I-I've tried
to call you a thousand times.

25:17.020 --> 25:20.060
Is Matty okay?
Where is he?
He's fine.

25:20.120 --> 25:21.860
Everything is fine.

25:21.920 --> 25:24.890
What are you doing
in San Francisco?
Put him on the phone.

25:24.960 --> 25:28.130
Hey, why are you
acting this way?
Because you disappeared,

25:28.190 --> 25:30.690
and I haven't seen my son
in a month!

25:30.760 --> 25:33.730
I-I was just about
to call you.
Oh, bullshit!

25:33.800 --> 25:36.400
How can you move
and not tell me, Angie?

25:36.470 --> 25:38.640
We were coming
to see you next week.

25:38.710 --> 25:41.280
Just put Matty
on the phone.

25:41.340 --> 25:45.770
[ Sighs ]

25:45.850 --> 25:48.890
Matty?
It's Mommy.
Come say hi.

25:51.380 --> 25:53.480
Come here.
Here.

25:53.550 --> 25:57.380
- Hi, Mommy.
- Hello, sweetie pie.

25:57.460 --> 25:59.630
How are you, Matty?

25:59.690 --> 26:02.190
[ Laughs ]
I think about you
all the time, honey.

26:02.260 --> 26:07.290
- I miss you so much.
Are you doing okay, kiddo?
- I love you.

26:07.370 --> 26:12.440
Listen, Matty.
I know that this
has been really hard,

26:12.500 --> 26:15.640
but Angie is gonna bring you up
to see me next week, okay?

26:15.710 --> 26:17.780
Yes, Mommy.

26:17.840 --> 26:21.040
- Daddy!
- Nick?

26:24.420 --> 26:26.290
[ No Audible Speech ]

26:26.350 --> 26:28.880
Nick?

26:34.830 --> 26:37.670
[ Prisoners' Voices
Echoing ]

26:37.730 --> 26:39.760
[ Shocked Gasping ]

26:42.370 --> 26:44.240
[ Coins Rattling ]

26:46.710 --> 26:48.810
[ Sighs ]

26:53.510 --> 26:55.640
[ Line Beeping
Rapidly ]

26:58.420 --> 27:00.260
[ Hangs Up ]

27:05.420 --> 27:08.360
[ Prisoners'
Voices Echoing ]

27:45.130 --> 27:47.130
He was in San Francisco
last night.

27:47.200 --> 27:50.510
I have a phone number,
but it's already
been disconnected.

27:50.570 --> 27:53.880
No, I don't--
I don't have
a forwarding address.

27:53.940 --> 27:57.040
He's gone.
Well, don't you have
investigators?

27:57.110 --> 28:01.050
Doesn't your company
want to get its
$2 million back?

28:01.110 --> 28:04.480
Why aren't you
listening to me?
I am innocent.

28:04.550 --> 28:06.450
[ Prisoners Yelling ]
Yeah, you are.
Sure, you are.

28:09.120 --> 28:11.020
Hurry up.

28:14.260 --> 28:18.160
** [ "We Wish You
A Merry Christmas"
Over P.A. ]

28:23.240 --> 28:25.140
Put some elbow grease
behind that stirring.

28:25.200 --> 28:27.430
Nobody wants to eat
any burnt tapioca.

28:27.510 --> 28:29.710
Does it smell
like it's burning?

28:29.780 --> 28:32.950
Oh, I swear you got
shit for brains, girl.

28:33.010 --> 28:35.780
You're in prison.
Do you get that?

28:35.850 --> 28:37.820
Nobody wants to listen
to anybody in prison,

28:37.880 --> 28:39.680
so you can
just forget about
reopening your case,

28:39.750 --> 28:41.680
or a jailhouse appeal.

28:41.750 --> 28:43.820
You got that?

28:43.890 --> 28:47.450
They take years...
and they're 95%
unsuccessful.

28:47.530 --> 28:49.730
So, if you want
my advice--

28:49.800 --> 28:51.470
- No.
- Well, you're gonna get it.

28:51.530 --> 28:54.760
- You do your time.
- So what are you now,
a lawyer?

28:56.740 --> 28:58.810
Once upon a time.

29:00.040 --> 29:02.050
But they tend
to disbar murderers.

29:02.110 --> 29:05.780
And here's your
Christmas present.
You ready?

29:05.850 --> 29:09.850
Pay attention, because
this is best goddamn advice
you ever gonna get.

29:09.920 --> 29:13.060
Ever hear of double jeopardy?
Fifth amendment
to the constitution?

29:13.120 --> 29:15.590
Huh? No?
Well, double jeopardy
provides that,

29:15.650 --> 29:19.490
"No person may be tried
for the same crime twice."
You got that?

29:19.560 --> 29:23.270
Keep stirrin'.
The state says you already
killed your husband.

29:23.330 --> 29:25.900
They can't convict you
of it a second time.

29:25.970 --> 29:27.770
That means that
when you leave here,

29:27.830 --> 29:31.600
you track him down,
and when you find him
you can kill him.

29:31.670 --> 29:36.040
That's right.
You can walk right up to him
in Times Square,

29:36.110 --> 29:38.780
put a gun to his head
and pull the fuckin' trigger,

29:38.850 --> 29:42.020
and there's nothin'
anybody can do about it.

29:43.520 --> 29:46.920
Kinda makes you feel
warm and tingly all over,
don't it?

29:48.890 --> 29:51.430
That's right.
Keep stirrin'.

30:00.900 --> 30:03.900
[ Grunting ]

30:04.900 --> 30:07.400
[ Exhales ]

30:10.010 --> 30:12.150
[ Thunderclap ]

30:16.450 --> 30:20.560
I gotta hand it to you, honey.
It's just sheer hate
driving you on.

30:34.900 --> 30:38.770
Honey, the only way you're gonna
look like that is if I staple
the picture to your forehead.

30:38.840 --> 30:41.050
Just trust me, okay?

30:46.650 --> 30:50.450
- Matty's eighth
birthday, honey.
- [ Women ] Aw.

30:50.520 --> 30:52.520
Oh--
Look at that.

31:01.860 --> 31:03.930
[ Cheers, Applause ]

31:16.110 --> 31:19.050
You know, Evelyn,
I read that even if a child...

31:19.110 --> 31:23.180
is separated from its mother
the day it's born,

31:23.250 --> 31:25.660
it never forgets her voice.

31:26.820 --> 31:28.660
Think that's true?

31:32.460 --> 31:34.330
'Course I do.

31:38.660 --> 31:41.400
I feel like I've grown
these past six years.

31:41.470 --> 31:43.410
"Grown"? Honey,
they don't want
to hear...

31:43.470 --> 31:45.510
that you've turned
into some kind
of tree, okay?

31:45.570 --> 31:48.770
So just repeat after me:
"If I could trade places
with my husband, I would."

31:48.840 --> 31:51.210
Ugh.
"If I could trade places
with my husband, I would."

31:51.280 --> 31:53.120
That's good.
Now throw in a lot of
that born-again-Jesus stuff.

31:53.180 --> 31:55.050
They like that.
Listen, listen, listen.

31:55.110 --> 31:57.140
I want you to start
with this--

31:57.220 --> 31:59.560
"I'm not sitting
in front of you today
to make excuses."

31:59.620 --> 32:03.590
I'm not sitting
in front of you today
to try to make any excuses.

32:03.660 --> 32:06.300
I killed my husband.

32:06.360 --> 32:10.030
I've had to live
with that every day
for the past six years.

32:10.100 --> 32:12.640
But I swear to you
that I'm a changed person.

32:12.700 --> 32:18.180
Why should we believe you?
I don't think I can
ask you to believe me.

32:18.240 --> 32:21.710
All I can really do
is believe in myself,

32:21.770 --> 32:26.270
and know that if I were
given a chance, I could do
something good with my life.

32:26.350 --> 32:29.290
Make up for the wrong I did.

32:30.420 --> 32:33.220
[ Chattering,
Horns Blowing ]

32:50.100 --> 32:52.900
[ Man ]
That was cool.
Oh, mom-my!

32:52.970 --> 32:55.600
Yeah!
Hey, hey. Talk to me.
[ Laughs ]

32:55.670 --> 32:57.470
Oh, man,
did you see that?

32:58.980 --> 33:02.190
[ Man Talking,
Indistinct ]

33:04.920 --> 33:07.260
[ Man Continues ]
...six years telling
each other stories...

33:07.320 --> 33:09.730
about all the shit
that's been done to you.

33:09.790 --> 33:12.100
A lot of shit's
been done to you.
I know that.

33:12.160 --> 33:16.230
But let's imagine that
all those people that did
that shit showed up here.

33:16.300 --> 33:19.240
The man's
across the hall.
Thanks.

33:19.300 --> 33:21.040
Let's imagine that
they all showed up here
and apologized.

33:21.100 --> 33:24.030
Would that
change the situation
you're in right now?

33:24.100 --> 33:26.070
[ Continues,
Indistinct ]

33:28.040 --> 33:31.070
[ Man On Radio ] There's
the windup, and the pitch--
Come in.

33:31.140 --> 33:33.410
Ball two.
[ Continues, Indistinct ]

33:34.550 --> 33:36.420
[ Sighs ]

33:40.350 --> 33:43.620
- I'm Elizabeth Parsons.
- What do you have
in that box?

33:49.630 --> 33:51.500
Elizabeth Parsons.

33:53.430 --> 33:56.460
The state of Washington
has granted you
a conditional parole.

33:56.540 --> 33:59.410
For the next three years,
you will observe all
the rules of this facility,

33:59.470 --> 34:02.870
which means no fighting,
no fornicating,
no drinking, no drugs,

34:02.940 --> 34:04.870
no exceptions,
no excuses.

34:04.940 --> 34:07.810
Do you understand that?
Yes.

34:07.880 --> 34:09.690
This is your
social security card.

34:09.750 --> 34:13.990
You will find gainful
and sustained
employment.

34:14.050 --> 34:15.980
You are not
to carry a firearm
or a weapon of any kind,

34:16.050 --> 34:18.190
especially a knife.

34:18.260 --> 34:20.430
Curfew is at 8:30.

34:20.490 --> 34:23.790
This is
my cell phone number.
Do not lose it.

34:23.860 --> 34:26.160
If you think there's
a chance you will be
even five minutes late,

34:26.230 --> 34:27.490
you will call me,
I will have you picked up.

34:27.570 --> 34:29.510
Do you understand that?
Good.

34:29.570 --> 34:32.140
Any violation
of these conditions...

34:32.200 --> 34:35.940
and your
"get out of jail free" card
will be revoked by me,

34:36.010 --> 34:38.950
and you will return to prison
to serve the remainder of your
sentence and maybe then some.

34:39.010 --> 34:41.380
Look right here.
[ Clicks, Whirs ]

34:47.290 --> 34:49.990
[ Radio Announcer Continues,
Indistinct ]

34:50.060 --> 34:52.660
[ Sighs, Grunts ]

34:54.430 --> 34:56.930
Is this
a problem for you?

34:57.000 --> 35:01.000
- No.
- Yes, it is. Do you want
to tell me about him?

35:01.070 --> 35:03.140
No.

35:03.200 --> 35:05.630
[ Scoffs ]
No.

35:05.700 --> 35:07.670
I'm gonna have trouble
with you, Parsons.

35:07.740 --> 35:09.880
No, sir.
No, you're not.
I learned my lesson.

35:09.940 --> 35:11.870
I just want to--
I'm not interested
in your goddamn contrition.

35:11.940 --> 35:14.510
I'm interested in your behavior.
Get out of here
and behave yourself.

35:14.580 --> 35:16.980
You're in room eight
on the second floor.

35:17.050 --> 35:19.460
[ Keys Jingling ]

35:21.120 --> 35:23.730
[ Radio Volume Increases ]

35:23.790 --> 35:26.400
[ Door Opens ]

35:46.910 --> 35:48.680
No, you're, uh--
[ Chuckles ]

35:48.750 --> 35:50.850
You're never gonna
get anywhere like that.

35:50.920 --> 35:53.620
Here.
[ Tapping Keyboard ]

35:55.120 --> 35:58.020
[ Beeps ]

35:58.090 --> 36:00.060
Hmm. Nice shampoo.

36:00.130 --> 36:03.300
What are you looking for?
A friend I haven't seen
for a couple of years.

36:03.360 --> 36:05.230
Someone said
I should try the Internet.

36:05.300 --> 36:08.210
This a boy...
friend?

36:08.270 --> 36:11.410
Girl.
Okay. Well, in that case,
I'll help you.

36:11.470 --> 36:14.370
[ Chuckles ]
Does your friend
have E-mail?

36:14.440 --> 36:18.140
I have no idea.
Okay, come on.
Let's do some surfing.

36:18.210 --> 36:21.170
- So, what's
your friend's name?
- Angela Green.

36:21.250 --> 36:23.750
Uh, zip code?

36:23.820 --> 36:26.260
Hmm. How about
a social security number?

36:26.320 --> 36:29.030
That way we could run
a credit report, and it'll
give us her address.

36:29.090 --> 36:33.160
Nope.
She was a school teacher.

36:33.230 --> 36:35.230
Done deal.
[ Tapping Keyboard ]

36:43.130 --> 36:45.470
[ Man ]
And... voila.
[ Beeps ]

36:47.240 --> 36:50.780
Now, maybe when this thing
has finished its searching,
we could go to this, uh,

36:50.840 --> 36:54.510
this neat little bar
I know and, uh, you know,
have a little drink.

36:55.850 --> 36:57.820
What do you say?
Yeah.

36:57.880 --> 37:00.710
I just have to check in
with my parole officer first.

37:03.960 --> 37:07.200
You've been to jail?
Actually, prison.
Jail is a different thing.

37:07.260 --> 37:10.900
[ Laughing ]
So, what did you do, not pay
your parking tickets?

37:10.960 --> 37:14.930
Oh, no.
I was convicted
of murdering my husband.

37:17.170 --> 37:19.080
[ Chuckling ]
You're kidding, right?

37:19.140 --> 37:23.350
No, I'm not.
Um, "sliced and diced,"
the paper called it.

37:23.410 --> 37:25.450
Can you believe that?

37:26.910 --> 37:28.780
You're not kidding?

37:28.850 --> 37:32.060
No. I said I wasn't.
But it would be nice
to have a drink.

37:32.120 --> 37:34.260
I haven't been out
in a long time.
[ Chuckles ]

37:35.190 --> 37:37.230
Ye-- Oh!

37:37.290 --> 37:39.230
Oh, look, I just
remembered I have, um,

37:39.290 --> 37:41.290
this appointment
with the--
See ya.

37:41.360 --> 37:42.960
See ya. Sorry.

37:44.530 --> 37:48.630
Oh. Book.
See ya.
[ Clears Throat ]

37:50.840 --> 37:52.780
[ Beeps ]

37:53.970 --> 37:55.900
Oh, my God.
[ Sighs ]

37:59.580 --> 38:03.090
So he takes me out for dinner,
and he feeds me escargot.
Do you know what those are?

38:03.150 --> 38:05.690
Yeah.
Snails. Snails, yuck.

38:05.750 --> 38:07.650
But anyway, the moment
I go to bed with him,

38:07.720 --> 38:09.830
the big asshole
dumps me.
Geez, man.

38:09.890 --> 38:12.730
[ Woman ]
Oh, for Christ's sake,
you nit-picking fuck!

38:12.790 --> 38:14.690
[ Parole Officer ]
Ruby, do not insult me
by raising your voice.

38:14.760 --> 38:16.620
I'm standing right here,
and I can hear you just fine.

38:16.700 --> 38:19.800
[ Ruby ] All right. Sorry.
By the way, I don't like it
when you call me dirty names.

38:19.870 --> 38:21.940
Please, Mr. Lehman,
don't do this to me.
I didn't do nothing!

38:22.000 --> 38:24.930
[ Lehman ]
Where were you this afternoon?
I was at my job.

38:25.000 --> 38:28.070
You were down on Pike Street
wearing lime-green hot pants
and fishnet stockings!

38:28.140 --> 38:31.150
I was on my way to work!
At McDonald's?
In those clothes?

38:31.210 --> 38:33.450
You haven't been
to work in a week!
Get your stuff.

38:33.510 --> 38:36.640
Look, I-I'm sorry, man.
I won't do it again.

38:36.720 --> 38:38.690
I will never do
that shit again.
I promise that.

38:38.750 --> 38:40.850
You blew off your parole.
You're going back.
It's that simple.

38:40.920 --> 38:43.290
[ Women Sigh, Groan ]

38:43.360 --> 38:46.160
You fuck.
You fuckin' cocksucker!

38:46.220 --> 38:49.020
You got
a dirty mouth, Ruby!
I want one chance!

38:49.090 --> 38:51.290
I just want one chance!

38:51.360 --> 38:53.690
Goddamn you,
motherfucker!

38:53.770 --> 38:55.940
You son of a bitch.
You mean fucker.

38:56.000 --> 38:59.070
You send me back there
it'll kill me,
you mean son of a bitch!

38:59.140 --> 39:01.810
[ Guard ] Come on.
Fuck you!
Fucking asshole!

39:01.870 --> 39:05.070
[ Murmuring ]
Show's over. Go to sleep!

39:12.520 --> 39:14.490
You think I'm
a mean son of a bitch?

39:14.550 --> 39:17.280
I think you could have
given her a second chance.

39:17.360 --> 39:19.900
There are no second chances
in this house, baby.
This is the last chance house.

39:19.960 --> 39:22.870
You try to understand that.
[ Woman ]
Yeah. Yeah, we got it.

39:22.930 --> 39:25.170
What the hell is wrong
with that guy?

39:25.230 --> 39:28.630
What I heard,
the man used to be some
college whatchamacallit.

39:28.700 --> 39:31.030
Law teacher or something?
Yeah, that's right.
That's right.

39:31.100 --> 39:35.170
You're kidding.
How does a law professor
end up someplace like this?

39:35.240 --> 39:37.270
'Cause life's a bitch.
Bitch, my ass.

39:37.340 --> 39:39.810
He got a D.U.I.
and totalled his car.

39:39.880 --> 39:42.420
I heard he totalled
his wife and his daughter
in that accident.

39:42.480 --> 39:44.580
Girl, you're
talkin' shit.
Nobody got killed.

39:44.650 --> 39:47.610
But by the time his wife
got done with him, I bet
he wished he was dead.

39:47.690 --> 39:50.560
Took everything he had.
Including the kid.

39:50.620 --> 39:52.790
Hasn't seen his girl
in years.

40:37.640 --> 40:39.510
Libby, it's wrong of you
to be here.

40:39.570 --> 40:43.670
It's very wrong.
I'm sorry to bother you,
but you're my only hope.

40:43.740 --> 40:46.470
Sharon? No, you put
that down, please.

40:46.550 --> 40:48.450
Libby, I'm sorry.
I can't.

40:48.510 --> 40:51.210
I want to find my son!

40:51.280 --> 40:53.050
Matty's had
six years with Angie.

40:53.120 --> 40:55.860
I mean, think about it,
Libby-- six years.

40:55.920 --> 40:58.850
Oh, Benjamin,
that's a great sand castle.

40:58.920 --> 41:01.020
If you come back
into his life right now,

41:01.090 --> 41:03.920
it's just gonna cause
more disruption and pain.

41:04.000 --> 41:07.670
Just think about it,
Libby, please?
Think about it.

41:07.730 --> 41:10.400
I just want to see him,
Rebecca.

41:10.470 --> 41:13.540
[ Sighs ]
Can you give me an address
for Angie, so I can see him?

41:13.610 --> 41:17.080
Look, I'm sorry.
I really am sorry.

41:19.110 --> 41:22.610
Lauren?
Come on, get down,
please. That's it.

41:27.590 --> 41:29.660
[ Footsteps ]

41:33.660 --> 41:35.900
[ Dog Barking ]

41:45.670 --> 41:48.700
[ Barking Continues ]

42:02.590 --> 42:04.600
[ Knocking ]

42:07.290 --> 42:11.760
Where's Parsons?
[ Sighs ]
I don't know. Not here.

42:28.980 --> 42:31.610
[ Sighs, Grunts ]
[ File Cabinet Rattling ]

42:37.320 --> 42:39.320
[ Vehicle Pulling Up ]

42:39.390 --> 42:41.250
[ Gasps ]

42:47.800 --> 42:50.670
[ Officer ]
Probably just a raccoon.

42:50.740 --> 42:52.340
[ Cabinet, Keys
Rattling ]

42:59.310 --> 43:02.310
[ Panting ]

43:15.960 --> 43:19.960
- [ Voices, Indistinct ]
- [ Police Radio Chatter ]

43:26.170 --> 43:28.200
[ Officer ]
Check up the stairs.

43:33.750 --> 43:35.790
[ Doorknob Rattling ]

43:45.860 --> 43:48.670
Cutter! Up here!

43:54.030 --> 43:55.930
Shit!

43:57.870 --> 43:59.780
[ Grunts ]
I got her.

44:24.300 --> 44:27.140
There she is.

44:27.200 --> 44:29.940
[ Panting ]

44:36.640 --> 44:38.740
[ Grunts ]

44:54.390 --> 44:58.090
[ Both Screaming ]

45:00.370 --> 45:02.940
Shit!
[ Grunting ]

45:22.450 --> 45:25.090
Ohh!

45:25.160 --> 45:28.770
[ Libby Screams,
Grunts ]

45:32.260 --> 45:35.500
Jesus Christ, Libby,
what are you doing here?

45:52.950 --> 45:55.980
[ Lock Turns,
Door Opens ]

45:56.050 --> 45:58.080
[ Door Squeaking ]

46:11.200 --> 46:14.200
Did you have a nice day
at the beach?

46:15.670 --> 46:17.500
[ Buoy Bell Clanging ]

46:21.180 --> 46:23.190
You piss me off,
Parsons.

46:29.290 --> 46:31.930
Angela Green--
that's the woman that's
got your kid, right?

46:31.990 --> 46:35.290
Can we not talk,
please, Lehman?

46:35.360 --> 46:37.190
Okay.
All right.

46:37.260 --> 46:39.760
So why'd she skip town?
She just skipped town.

46:39.830 --> 46:41.790
Yeah, with your husband,
who isn't dead...

46:41.870 --> 46:43.770
'cause you didn't
kill him?
[ Chuckles ]

46:43.840 --> 46:45.680
Bullshit.
Okay,
I killed my husband.

46:45.740 --> 46:48.510
I chopped him up
into little bits,
and dumped him in the Pacific.

46:48.570 --> 46:50.470
- Are you satisfied?
- No. No.

46:50.540 --> 46:53.640
You were a hell of a lot closer
to your kid three days ago
than you are today.

46:53.710 --> 46:57.440
All you had to do
was wait three years.
That's all.

46:57.520 --> 47:00.220
You fucking idiot.

47:02.750 --> 47:05.220
You cannot know
what it is like to sit
in prison for six years...

47:05.290 --> 47:08.290
and think of nothing else
in the world but your son.

47:08.360 --> 47:10.200
Did I make the right choice?
You ask the wrong question,
Lehman.

47:10.260 --> 47:12.230
I didn't have a choice.
Fuck your curfew!

47:22.210 --> 47:24.850
Who's that? Your daughter?

47:28.150 --> 47:30.420
Is that a problem
for you, Lehman?

47:32.020 --> 47:34.460
I'm going up top.

47:48.130 --> 47:50.200
Don't go anywhere.

47:55.910 --> 47:57.950
[ Horn Blows ]

48:01.450 --> 48:03.290
[ People Chattering ]

48:29.540 --> 48:31.370
[ Chattering Continues ]

48:32.640 --> 48:34.610
[ Woman ]
Janey, honey,
read your book.

48:37.880 --> 48:40.180
[ Engine Starts ]

48:43.590 --> 48:45.530
[ Tires Squealing ]

48:46.690 --> 48:49.160
Oh! Shit!

49:07.650 --> 49:10.950
- [ Tires Squealing ]
- [ Chattering ]

49:19.160 --> 49:21.200
[ People Chattering,
Laughing ]

49:44.950 --> 49:47.190
[ Tires Screeching ]

49:49.620 --> 49:52.290
[ Groans ]

49:54.360 --> 49:56.200
[ Gasps ]

49:59.160 --> 50:01.360
[ Grunting ]

50:03.100 --> 50:05.600
[ Screams ]

50:05.670 --> 50:08.500
[ Screeching ]

50:18.150 --> 50:22.490
- Oh, my God!
- [ Chattering ]

50:22.550 --> 50:24.720
[ Alarm Sounding ]

50:26.290 --> 50:28.650
[ Alarm Bell Ringing ]

50:33.330 --> 50:35.400
[ Grunting, Gasping ]

51:08.070 --> 51:10.840
[ Both Gasping ]

51:13.670 --> 51:16.100
[ Cries Out ]

51:26.450 --> 51:28.310
[ Screams ]
[ Groans ]

51:28.390 --> 51:33.230
[ Panting, Gasping ]

51:53.510 --> 51:55.380
[ Gasping ]

52:06.260 --> 52:08.600
I got him!
Grab ahold for me.

52:16.330 --> 52:18.800
[ Man ]
O-2 ready.

52:18.870 --> 52:21.780
- [ Man ]
Is he all right?
- I guess he's all right.

52:38.920 --> 52:40.790
[ Karl ]
Did you voluntarily
give her the gun?

52:40.860 --> 52:42.830
Come on, Karl.
What do you think?
Hey! Hey.

52:42.890 --> 52:44.720
Sorry.
Were you drinking?

52:44.800 --> 52:47.500
No, I wasn't drinking.
It's been known
to happen.

52:47.570 --> 52:49.910
Do you have any idea
where she's gone?
No.

52:49.970 --> 52:51.940
All right.
Well, that's about all,
then, isn't it?

52:52.000 --> 52:53.870
All what?

52:53.940 --> 52:55.880
There'll be
an investigation into
your actions today.

52:55.940 --> 52:58.970
I wouldn't hold my breath
about the prospect
of keeping your job.

52:59.040 --> 53:01.770
Karl, give me a break.
Goddamn.

53:03.150 --> 53:05.220
Thanks a lot.

53:15.890 --> 53:17.790
[ Digging ]

53:17.860 --> 53:20.460
[ Woman ]
Sent your father
off to the V.F.W.

53:20.530 --> 53:23.030
He'll be playing gin
for hours.

53:23.100 --> 53:25.630
Some things never change.
Oh!

53:25.700 --> 53:28.130
He's not as bad
as he used to be,
you know.

53:28.210 --> 53:30.250
I'm glad for you,
Mama.

53:41.990 --> 53:45.500
I always said
there was good money
in tomatoes.

53:50.300 --> 53:52.370
[ Laughs ]

54:11.620 --> 54:13.660
So. You're in the market
for a B.M.W.?

54:13.720 --> 54:17.230
Yeah. Who isn't?
Well, they're the best.

54:17.290 --> 54:19.700
I decided it was finally
time to trade up.

54:19.760 --> 54:21.700
Right.

54:21.760 --> 54:24.370
So why don't you
check my credit and see
if I can finance this.

54:24.430 --> 54:26.340
Great. Let me have
your social security number,

54:26.400 --> 54:28.400
and I'll get the ball
rolling.

54:39.440 --> 54:41.310
Twenty Oriole Terrace,
Evergreen, Colorado.

54:41.380 --> 54:43.420
Is that your
current address?

54:43.480 --> 54:46.710
Twenty Oriole Terrace,
Evergreen, Colorado?
Sure is.

54:46.780 --> 54:50.180
Didn't you say your name
was Angela Green?
'Cause this says Ryder.

54:50.250 --> 54:54.550
- Oh, no. I said Ryder.
Angela Ryder.
- What about the car?

54:56.560 --> 54:59.630
Here. Fill this out
and come back to me.

54:59.700 --> 55:04.270
- How's tricks, Orbe?
- No way.

55:04.340 --> 55:06.710
No way, no way.
I've been clean, Mr. Travis.

55:06.770 --> 55:08.970
Oh, I know.
I believe you. I do.

55:09.040 --> 55:11.080
What I need is a search
on a lady named Angela Green.

55:11.140 --> 55:13.840
I've got her
social security number here.
I'd like you to--

55:13.910 --> 55:16.110
Please. You know I'm
not allowed to give out
personal information.

55:16.180 --> 55:18.140
Oh, I'm so--
I shouldn't have asked
you that. I'm sorry.

55:18.220 --> 55:20.260
Uh-huh.

55:20.320 --> 55:22.220
Speaking of giving out
personal information,
does your employer know...

55:22.290 --> 55:24.260
you used to perform
the art of fellatio
for a living,

55:24.320 --> 55:26.650
went to prison for it,
and now you're out on parole?
Okay. Okay. Shut up.

55:26.720 --> 55:28.920
You're required by law
to tell him.
All right. Okay.

55:28.990 --> 55:30.860
[ Sighs ]

55:32.300 --> 55:34.940
You're looking good, Orbe.

55:35.000 --> 55:36.870
I know.

57:12.460 --> 57:14.630
[ Doorbell Rings ]

57:14.700 --> 57:16.910
[ Hammer Clicks ]

57:21.340 --> 57:23.850
[ Woman ]
Honey, can you get that?

57:29.080 --> 57:31.190
Hi.

57:37.220 --> 57:40.890
- [ Woman ]
Who is it, Sam?
- Uh, some lady.

57:42.390 --> 57:46.330
- May I help you?
- I'm looking for
my friend, Angela Ryder.

57:46.400 --> 57:50.240
- I thought
this was her address.
- I've never heard of her.

57:50.300 --> 57:53.500
But we've just moved in.
Maybe you should check
with the woman next door.

57:53.570 --> 57:55.670
She's been here 40 years.

57:55.740 --> 58:01.540
Excuse me.
Dearie, whatever you're selling,
I've already got two of them.

58:03.210 --> 58:05.440
I'm just looking
for my friend, Angela Ryder.

58:05.520 --> 58:08.020
She used to live
next door.

58:08.090 --> 58:11.960
Oh, I--
I'm sorry to be
the one to tell you.

58:12.020 --> 58:14.850
but Angie died
in the accident.

58:15.990 --> 58:19.490
I-It was three
or four years ago.

58:19.560 --> 58:21.360
It was one of those
awful things. The--

58:21.430 --> 58:25.030
The, uh, stove,
the gas stove
in their house was leaking.

58:25.100 --> 58:27.800
The explosion knocked out
some of my windows,

58:27.870 --> 58:30.440
and, uh--
What about the boy?

58:30.510 --> 58:32.980
Matty?
He's such a dear child.

58:33.040 --> 58:35.840
No, he and Simon
weren't there
when it happened.

58:37.250 --> 58:39.190
Poor Simon.

58:39.250 --> 58:43.190
I've never seen anyone
so... grief stricken.

58:43.250 --> 58:45.820
Oh, I'm sure.

58:45.890 --> 58:47.850
[ Indistinct Announcements
Over P.A. ]

58:54.360 --> 58:57.160
[ Whirring, Clicking ]

59:12.420 --> 59:14.260
Help me out, kiddo.

59:20.630 --> 59:23.070
It would really help
if you could remember...

59:23.130 --> 59:25.100
what kind of car
she was driving.

59:25.160 --> 59:28.030
Well, it was
an old truck.
Yeah?

59:28.100 --> 59:30.540
It's, um--
I don't know what year
or make or anything.

59:30.600 --> 59:32.770
Well, what color
was it?

59:59.160 --> 1:00:02.730
Kandinsky?
It's a bit out
of our reach, I'm afraid.

1:00:02.800 --> 1:00:05.800
I have a few Picasso
and Chagall lithographs.

1:00:05.870 --> 1:00:07.770
Mm, no.
It-It's Kandinsky...

1:00:07.840 --> 1:00:10.710
that I'm particularly
interested in, especially
his Blue Rider period.

1:00:10.780 --> 1:00:14.620
- I love that.
- Uh, well, uh--

1:00:14.680 --> 1:00:16.920
Let's check Art Scan.

1:00:18.950 --> 1:00:22.120
Kandinskys don't become
available too often,
I'm afraid.

1:00:23.590 --> 1:00:25.430
Here's a lovely little Miro.

1:00:25.490 --> 1:00:28.630
It's quite reasonable.
It really needs
to be Kandinsky.

1:00:28.690 --> 1:00:31.090
Kandinsky... yes.

1:00:32.300 --> 1:00:36.440
Ah! Here is a lovely
1922 Kandinsky lithograph.

1:00:36.500 --> 1:00:39.400
It's not quite the--
The 1911 is all
that interests me.

1:00:39.470 --> 1:00:41.380
1911...

1:00:51.550 --> 1:00:55.460
Stop. There. Yes.
Yes, that's it.

1:00:55.520 --> 1:00:58.390
I'm afraid we've missed that.
It was sold to a museum
in Munich six months ago.

1:00:58.460 --> 1:01:01.400
Do you think you
could find who sold it?
Perhaps they have more.

1:01:02.790 --> 1:01:05.220
Well, uh, why, yes.
Yes, let's see.

1:01:07.160 --> 1:01:10.530
[ Bell Dings ]

1:01:10.600 --> 1:01:13.030
If you'll excuse me
a moment.

1:01:18.740 --> 1:01:21.010
Yes, sir.
Can I help you?

1:01:21.080 --> 1:01:23.490
Yes. My name
is Travis Lehman.

1:01:23.550 --> 1:01:26.420
[ Continues, Muffled ]

1:01:30.990 --> 1:01:33.430
[ Travis Continues Speaking,
Indistinct ]

1:01:40.200 --> 1:01:42.300
[ Travis ]
Actually, I'm looking
for a young lady.

1:01:52.480 --> 1:01:55.180
[ Beeps ]

1:02:06.820 --> 1:02:09.490
[ Tires Squealing ]

1:02:09.560 --> 1:02:13.040
[ All Clamoring ]

1:02:21.140 --> 1:02:23.410
[ Tires Screeching,
Horns Honking ]

1:02:51.740 --> 1:02:54.140
She seemed so refined.

1:02:54.200 --> 1:02:57.770
I would really like to know
what that woman wanted
in your gallery.

1:03:07.120 --> 1:03:11.530
[ Men Singing A Capella ]
* Amazing *

1:03:11.590 --> 1:03:14.500
* Grace *

1:03:14.560 --> 1:03:18.370
* How sweet *

1:03:18.430 --> 1:03:20.540
* The sound *

1:03:21.970 --> 1:03:25.640
* That saved *

1:03:25.700 --> 1:03:29.370
* A wretch *

1:03:29.440 --> 1:03:35.050
* Like me **

1:04:20.690 --> 1:04:23.090
Can I help you?

1:04:25.460 --> 1:04:27.490
I'm looking
for Jonathan Devereaux.

1:04:27.560 --> 1:04:31.360
Mr. Devereaux is out
right now. He'll be back
tonight for the party.

1:04:31.440 --> 1:04:35.950
- Well, is Matty here?
- I don't believe
I know you, ma'am.

1:04:36.010 --> 1:04:38.580
Maybe you'd like
to leave a message.

1:04:40.440 --> 1:04:42.270
[ People Chattering ]

1:05:00.970 --> 1:05:03.110
[ Man ]
It's certainly a pleasure
having you stay with us...

1:05:03.170 --> 1:05:05.440
here at the Monteleone,
Mrs. Kritch.
[ Woman ] Thank you.

1:05:05.500 --> 1:05:09.100
My suite has a view?
Your room has a
lovely view, Mrs. Kritch.

1:05:09.170 --> 1:05:11.670
And I need a masseuse.
I'll send Jerome
right up.

1:05:11.740 --> 1:05:13.610
Bruce?

1:05:14.840 --> 1:05:16.610
Fourteen twenty--
Mrs. Kritch.

1:05:17.750 --> 1:05:20.220
Hello.

1:05:34.030 --> 1:05:36.530
I'm sorry.
Are you... lost?

1:05:36.600 --> 1:05:40.930
No. Actually, I'm found.
I just had an hour
with Jerome.

1:05:42.240 --> 1:05:44.910
Oh. Jerome.
I've heard that he
is marvelous.

1:05:44.980 --> 1:05:48.850
He's fabulous.
I haven't felt this good
since my husband died.

1:05:48.910 --> 1:05:53.050
So, I've got something
for tonight, but I think
I need Armani.

1:05:54.150 --> 1:05:56.550
Yes. Very good, Mrs.--

1:05:56.620 --> 1:05:58.580
Kritch. Suite 1420.

1:05:58.660 --> 1:06:00.900
Of course.

1:06:00.960 --> 1:06:03.170
I'll be charging it
to my room.

1:06:09.200 --> 1:06:12.910
- [ Beeps ]
- Hmm. Now, Mrs. Kritch,

1:06:12.970 --> 1:06:16.250
I would say that you
are a size... four?

1:06:16.310 --> 1:06:19.080
- A two.
- Of course.

1:06:30.190 --> 1:06:32.230
[ Man ]
There's a guy
waiting for you.

1:06:42.370 --> 1:06:44.970
Did you catch that thing?

1:06:45.040 --> 1:06:47.140
What did you use
for bait?

1:06:47.200 --> 1:06:49.930
I caught that big
bucket-mouth
son of a bitch...

1:06:50.010 --> 1:06:53.120
off an old rebel lure
my daddy left me.

1:06:53.180 --> 1:06:55.120
'Course there's buzz bombs,
poppers, jigs--

1:06:55.180 --> 1:06:58.090
all kinds of things work
back in these waters.

1:06:58.150 --> 1:07:02.690
- I'm Jim Mangold.
- Travis Lehman, Washington
Department of Corrections.

1:07:02.750 --> 1:07:04.580
What can I do for you?

1:07:05.790 --> 1:07:08.730
Who's this?
That's somebody
I'm looking for.

1:07:08.790 --> 1:07:10.690
Pretty girl.
Oh, yeah.

1:07:10.760 --> 1:07:13.590
She's very pretty,
for a convicted murderer.
[ Chuckles ]

1:07:14.730 --> 1:07:18.100
She jumped parole
on me.

1:07:19.300 --> 1:07:21.570
Mr. Lehman, I'd love
to be able to help you, sir.

1:07:21.640 --> 1:07:24.310
No, I don't want you guys
to go to any trouble.
I can handle matters.

1:07:24.370 --> 1:07:26.270
I just came down
as a professional courtesy,

1:07:26.340 --> 1:07:30.340
since she's in New Orleans,
and came here to kill one
of your prominent citizens.

1:07:30.410 --> 1:07:33.750
- And just how is she
planning on doing that?
- I don't know.

1:07:33.820 --> 1:07:37.330
She'll probably use
the .38 special
she stole from me.

1:07:40.120 --> 1:07:42.290
Roy Lee!

1:07:42.360 --> 1:07:44.800
Get these in the works--
now.

1:07:46.700 --> 1:07:49.140
She looks lovely.
Invitation, please.

1:07:49.200 --> 1:07:51.170
Enjoy your evening.

1:07:51.240 --> 1:07:53.740
Good evening.
Thank you.

1:07:56.070 --> 1:07:59.670
Invitations, please.
Yes, I need to see
your invitation.

1:08:03.210 --> 1:08:05.140
Enjoy your evening.

1:08:05.220 --> 1:08:07.390
Your invitation?

1:08:10.720 --> 1:08:13.080
Good evening.
What a remarkable wrap.

1:08:13.160 --> 1:08:15.000
Where on earth
did you find that?

1:08:15.060 --> 1:08:17.900
The first lady asked me
the same thing when we
stayed at the White House,

1:08:17.960 --> 1:08:20.090
and I wouldn't
tell her either.

1:08:20.160 --> 1:08:21.960
Your invitation, sir?
I got it right here.

1:08:22.030 --> 1:08:24.760
Enjoy your evening.
Good evening, miss.
Good evening.

1:08:24.830 --> 1:08:27.630
** [ Mid-Tempo Jazz ]

1:08:29.840 --> 1:08:32.410
* Mention of work
makes you go berserk **

1:08:32.480 --> 1:08:34.480
** [ Continues ]

1:09:19.360 --> 1:09:21.500
** [ Ends ]
[ Applause ]

1:09:25.530 --> 1:09:28.540
- Good evening,
mesdames and messieurs.
- [ Crowd ] Good evening!

1:09:28.600 --> 1:09:30.670
We're delighted to have you
with us this evening...

1:09:30.730 --> 1:09:35.400
on this very special occasion--
and, as is the custom
in New Orleans,

1:09:35.470 --> 1:09:39.940
- since even before the War
of Northern Aggression,
- [ Applause, Groans ]

1:09:40.010 --> 1:09:42.250
we offer the ladies
of this fair city
our first bachelor...

1:09:42.310 --> 1:09:46.880
to be put up
on the auction block,
our host, Jonathan Devereaux.

1:09:46.950 --> 1:09:49.280
[ Applause, Cheers ]

1:09:51.290 --> 1:09:54.330
Where is that man?
Where is that man?

1:09:55.260 --> 1:09:57.270
Hey, Jonathan.
Thank you, Louis.

1:09:58.190 --> 1:10:00.230
You all having a good time?

1:10:01.670 --> 1:10:04.670
Now then, ladies,
what you see before you...

1:10:04.730 --> 1:10:07.030
is a moderately presentable
man in his 30s,

1:10:07.100 --> 1:10:12.270
given to unhealthy thoughts
and a dissipated lifestyle...
[ Laughter ]

1:10:12.340 --> 1:10:15.240
with--
and this is what's gonna
cost you the really big money--

1:10:15.310 --> 1:10:17.310
[ Murmuring, Laughing ]

1:10:20.380 --> 1:10:22.880
absolutely no
redeeming moral virtue.

1:10:22.950 --> 1:10:25.980
[ Laughter, Applause ]

1:10:26.060 --> 1:10:29.860
- Five hundred.
- Dear woman, my cuff links
cost more than that.

1:10:29.930 --> 1:10:32.400
Do I hear a thousand?

1:10:32.460 --> 1:10:34.630
- A thousand.
- Thank you.

1:10:36.930 --> 1:10:40.230
- Mmm!
- Two thousand.

1:10:41.870 --> 1:10:44.140
All right, now, did I just hear
the voice of the charming
Miss Monroe?

1:10:44.210 --> 1:10:47.220
'Cause I was just starting
to worry-- beginning
to think you didn't care.

1:10:47.280 --> 1:10:49.880
[ Libby ]
Twenty-five hundred.

1:10:53.320 --> 1:10:56.390
Twenty-five hundred.
We have a new bidder.

1:10:56.450 --> 1:10:58.920
- Twenty-five hundred.
- Three thousand.

1:11:00.260 --> 1:11:02.960
- Five thousand.
- [ Man ]
Oh!

1:11:10.530 --> 1:11:13.000
Fifty-five hundred.

1:11:13.070 --> 1:11:15.640
[ Hooting, Murmuring ]

1:11:17.270 --> 1:11:20.510
We have fifty-five hundred.
Will, uh--

1:11:20.580 --> 1:11:22.580
Will the lady take us to six?

1:11:24.710 --> 1:11:28.310
- Ten thousand dollars.
- [ Crowd Exclaims ]

1:11:31.920 --> 1:11:35.720
Well, see, at last,
someone who knows my true value.

1:11:35.790 --> 1:11:38.560
Now, Miss Monroe,
I believe the bid...

1:11:38.630 --> 1:11:41.670
is to you at $10,500.

1:11:41.730 --> 1:11:43.760
Well, you can have him, honey.

1:11:43.830 --> 1:11:45.760
Believe me,
he ain't worth that much--

1:11:45.840 --> 1:11:47.840
I know
from personal experience.

1:11:47.900 --> 1:11:50.230
[ Groans, Laughter ]
Yeah. Thank you, honey.

1:11:50.310 --> 1:11:52.810
All right, going once.

1:11:52.880 --> 1:11:54.750
Going twice.

1:11:56.110 --> 1:11:59.180
Sold to the woman
in the back.

1:11:59.250 --> 1:12:01.090
Ten thousand dollars.

1:12:04.950 --> 1:12:07.620
Would you like
to come forward and claim
your prize, young lady?

1:12:14.860 --> 1:12:17.100
Hello, Nick.

1:12:23.840 --> 1:12:25.800
Well, aren't you
gonna give me a kiss?

1:12:28.010 --> 1:12:30.480
I think I've earned it.

1:12:33.420 --> 1:12:35.420
[ Crowd Murmuring,
Booing ]

1:12:39.960 --> 1:12:44.230
[ Applause, Cheers ]

1:12:44.290 --> 1:12:47.790
And now--
I'll make this real
easy for you, Nick.

1:12:47.860 --> 1:12:50.530
I'll make you an offer
you can't refuse.

1:12:50.600 --> 1:12:53.000
You used to love
a good deal,
didn't you?

1:12:53.070 --> 1:12:55.440
Can we just take this
someplace private?
I don't think so.

1:12:55.510 --> 1:12:57.750
I remember what happened
the last time we were alone.

1:12:57.810 --> 1:13:00.210
I don't believe we've met.
I'm Suzanne Monroe.
[ Sighs ]

1:13:00.280 --> 1:13:02.820
I'm Libby.
I'm his wife.

1:13:03.980 --> 1:13:05.940
Well, Jonathan!

1:13:06.020 --> 1:13:09.420
A minute ago a bachelor,
and now you're married.

1:13:09.490 --> 1:13:12.460
You don't waste any time.

1:13:12.520 --> 1:13:14.450
- You been
in New Orleans long?
- She's, uh--

1:13:14.520 --> 1:13:16.420
I'm just
passing through town
to pick up my child.

1:13:16.490 --> 1:13:18.320
- I'll be leaving very soon.
- How nice.

1:13:18.390 --> 1:13:20.220
We're finally putting
the past behind us
and moving on...

1:13:20.300 --> 1:13:23.870
- with our lives,
aren't we, Jonathan?
- Sure.

1:13:23.930 --> 1:13:26.000
I do have
one question, though.

1:13:26.070 --> 1:13:28.880
How long were Angie and you
fucking before you decided
to get rid of me?

1:13:28.940 --> 1:13:30.610
[ Clears Throat ]

1:13:32.780 --> 1:13:35.620
- Would you excuse us, please?
- Oh, yeah, sure.
Go ahead.

1:13:37.950 --> 1:13:39.950
Where is he, Nick?
Libby. Libby--

1:13:40.020 --> 1:13:42.090
You destroyed my life,
and I will destroy yours...

1:13:42.150 --> 1:13:43.980
unless you give me
Matty.

1:13:44.050 --> 1:13:46.990
That's all I want.
Listen. Let me
explain something to you.

1:13:47.060 --> 1:13:49.130
You have
to understand something.
We were going under.

1:13:49.190 --> 1:13:51.560
We were gonna lose everything.

1:13:51.630 --> 1:13:54.500
If I'd had any guts,
I would have killed myself,

1:13:54.560 --> 1:13:56.430
but I was trying
to protect you.

1:13:56.500 --> 1:13:59.630
That's why I got
the life insurance--
I would be out of the picture...

1:13:59.700 --> 1:14:02.230
and you and Matty
would be okay.

1:14:02.310 --> 1:14:05.550
And I-I just never believed
they would convict you.

1:14:06.980 --> 1:14:09.550
They did, Nick.

1:14:09.610 --> 1:14:12.680
And the thing with Angie
happened later.

1:14:12.750 --> 1:14:15.920
It was just--
It was a nightmare.

1:14:15.990 --> 1:14:18.390
And the worst part of it
was being away from you.

1:14:18.450 --> 1:14:21.020
So is that why
you killed her?

1:14:23.460 --> 1:14:26.870
- That was an accident.
- Nice try, Nick.
I'm not buying.

1:14:26.930 --> 1:14:29.690
It's bullshit.
I will swear
on the life of our son.

1:14:29.770 --> 1:14:33.170
Oh, don't you
fucking dare.

1:14:33.240 --> 1:14:36.650
You can keep your hotel,
your fancy accent
and your new name.

1:14:36.710 --> 1:14:39.280
- Just give me Matty.
- I understand.

1:14:39.340 --> 1:14:41.810
No. Now.
Give him to me now.

1:14:41.880 --> 1:14:43.820
Libby, it's
the middle of the night.
I can't just walk away.

1:14:43.880 --> 1:14:45.510
Do you think
I'm stupid?
No, I don't think you're stupid.

1:14:45.580 --> 1:14:48.950
-I won't let you
slip away once again.
-It's too far to Matty's school.

1:14:49.020 --> 1:14:52.960
- You've got to be patient.
- I've been patient
for six years.

1:14:53.020 --> 1:14:55.720
[ Man ]
Do I hear 2,000?
I want my child.

1:14:55.790 --> 1:14:58.820
Ah! Thank you.
You're a beautiful woman.

1:14:58.900 --> 1:15:02.540
I'll call you
tomorrow, Nick.
No screwing around.

1:15:02.600 --> 1:15:05.340
Going twice.
Okay, 2,000...

1:15:05.400 --> 1:15:08.930
for the lady in red.
Excuse me. Do you know
where Mr. Devereaux is?

1:15:09.010 --> 1:15:11.110
He's at the bar, sir.
Over here?

1:15:11.170 --> 1:15:13.040
Yes, sir.
Thank you.

1:15:13.110 --> 1:15:17.050
You ready to spend
some more money?
Who's gonna start us off?

1:15:17.110 --> 1:15:18.940
[ Auction Continues ]

1:15:22.690 --> 1:15:25.090
I'm sorry.
Oh, thank you, Marcel.

1:15:25.150 --> 1:15:27.250
Can I offer you
a drink?
Oh, no thanks.

1:15:27.320 --> 1:15:29.250
Wait a second.
Let me guess.

1:15:29.330 --> 1:15:31.530
I take you
for scotch and soda.

1:15:31.600 --> 1:15:34.200
Well, I'll have
a Diet Coke, please.

1:15:34.260 --> 1:15:37.060
Well, all right,
but I bet you used to drink
and now you're on the wagon.

1:15:37.130 --> 1:15:39.860
Ten dollars says I'm right.
You sure you've never
seen this woman before?

1:15:39.940 --> 1:15:42.010
No, I'm positive.
Okay.

1:15:42.070 --> 1:15:44.370
Let me get it straight.
She believes that I am
her husband--

1:15:44.440 --> 1:15:46.300
Oh, yeah.
Whom she killed.

1:15:46.380 --> 1:15:48.250
Yes, sir.

1:15:49.450 --> 1:15:51.220
That's-That's pretty
far-fetched.

1:15:51.280 --> 1:15:53.240
Far-fetched or not,
she is in New Orleans,

1:15:53.320 --> 1:15:55.560
she does have a gun
and she is looking for you.

1:15:55.620 --> 1:15:59.160
Well, thank you. I'll alert
our security people.
You do that.

1:15:59.220 --> 1:16:01.050
** [ Cajun ]

1:16:04.130 --> 1:16:05.970
** [ Continues ]

1:16:15.740 --> 1:16:18.010
Cops have been
passing these out.

1:16:22.210 --> 1:16:24.880
No reward. Screw 'em.

1:16:27.320 --> 1:16:30.460
You're gonna be posted
in every hotel in town.

1:16:30.520 --> 1:16:33.700
So much for
a good night's sleep.

1:16:40.500 --> 1:16:44.070
Take this.
Get out of here.

1:16:47.800 --> 1:16:49.870
Thanks a lot.

1:17:13.930 --> 1:17:15.890
** [ Dixieland ]

1:17:25.940 --> 1:17:28.410
Let's go, Lehman.
We spotted your girl.

1:17:46.500 --> 1:17:49.100
[ Bells Clanging ]

1:17:50.800 --> 1:17:53.770
[ Thunderclap ]
[ Whinnies ]

1:17:55.770 --> 1:17:58.100
** [ Cajun ]

1:18:01.510 --> 1:18:03.340
Where'd she go, Dilbert?

1:18:10.350 --> 1:18:12.250
Hey!

1:18:19.560 --> 1:18:21.390
** [ Dixieland ]

1:18:24.270 --> 1:18:26.240
Hey!

1:18:31.210 --> 1:18:33.210
** [ Country-Rock ]
Hey!

1:18:44.390 --> 1:18:47.500
** [ Blues ]

1:18:53.100 --> 1:18:55.770
** [ Rock And Roll ]

1:18:57.730 --> 1:18:59.830
Hey!

1:19:01.770 --> 1:19:04.700
- Hey!
- I'm sorry.

1:19:04.770 --> 1:19:06.740
- What do you think
you're doing?
- I'm very sorry, ma'am.

1:19:06.810 --> 1:19:09.870
I thought you were
somebody else. It was
a case of mistaken identity.

1:19:09.950 --> 1:19:13.420
Have a good evening.
I take it
that ain't her.

1:19:27.830 --> 1:19:30.060
[ Nick ]
Mr. Lehman.
[ Chuckles ]

1:19:30.130 --> 1:19:31.560
Come in.

1:19:31.630 --> 1:19:34.230
Thank you.
May I offer you
a Cuban cigar?

1:19:34.300 --> 1:19:36.600
Oh, no thanks.

1:19:36.670 --> 1:19:40.770
As you can see,
I'm alive and kicking.

1:19:40.840 --> 1:19:42.410
[ Chuckling ]
Yeah.

1:19:43.750 --> 1:19:45.520
So what can I do for you
this morning?

1:19:45.580 --> 1:19:48.480
We spotted the Parsons woman
in the Quarter last night.

1:19:48.550 --> 1:19:53.020
She got away.
I just came by to find out
if you'd heard from her.

1:19:53.090 --> 1:19:56.060
Not a peep.
Do you have any idea...

1:19:56.130 --> 1:19:59.230
why she's fixated
her lunacy on you?

1:19:59.300 --> 1:20:01.200
Well, the world's
full of crazy people,
am I right?

1:20:01.260 --> 1:20:03.260
[ Laughing ]
Oh, yes, you are right.

1:20:03.330 --> 1:20:06.300
Truer words
were never spoken.

1:20:07.540 --> 1:20:10.580
Those are nice pictures there.

1:20:10.640 --> 1:20:12.810
Did your kids do them?

1:20:13.740 --> 1:20:16.610
Uh, no.

1:20:16.680 --> 1:20:20.220
Those pictures are
by a very great artist
named Kandinsky.

1:20:20.280 --> 1:20:23.550
- Oh.
- But why do I think
you already knew that?

1:20:26.660 --> 1:20:30.230
- [ Telephone Rings ]
- Excuse me for a second.

1:20:31.360 --> 1:20:34.160
Yes?

1:20:36.830 --> 1:20:40.130
- This is a business call.
- Oh, I'm sorry.

1:20:40.200 --> 1:20:42.130
I hope you'll excuse me.
You let yourself out
that back door.

1:20:42.210 --> 1:20:45.680
It leads to the kitchen.
Get the chef to fix you
a New Orleans breakfast.

1:20:45.740 --> 1:20:47.710
Thanks.
I recommend
the Eggs St. Jacques.

1:20:47.780 --> 1:20:50.120
Oh, boy. That sounds good.
Mm-hmm.
I have your card.

1:20:50.180 --> 1:20:52.620
Okay.

1:20:55.250 --> 1:20:57.880
Morning, darlin'.
I hope you had a nice night.

1:20:57.950 --> 1:21:02.450
I want you to bring Matty
to Lafayette Cemetery
number three.

1:21:02.530 --> 1:21:05.470
A cemetery?
That's an odd choice
for a reunion.

1:21:05.530 --> 1:21:09.170
It's a big tourist place, Nick.
Lot of people around.

1:21:09.230 --> 1:21:13.030
You're a smart girl.
I can have him there by 4:00.

1:21:14.500 --> 1:21:17.900
** [ Jazz Band Playing
"St. James Infirmary" ]

1:21:53.380 --> 1:21:57.820
- Where's Matty?
- Relax. He's--
He was nervous.

1:21:57.880 --> 1:22:00.580
So I just told him
he could go play inside.

1:22:08.360 --> 1:22:10.900
There he is.

1:22:10.960 --> 1:22:13.220
Matty?
Come over here, son.

1:22:14.160 --> 1:22:16.890
Oh, geez. Matty--

1:22:16.970 --> 1:22:19.170
Okay, I'll get him
for you.
No! No.

1:22:20.170 --> 1:22:22.180
That's something
I want to do.

1:22:26.040 --> 1:22:27.970
Matty?

1:22:32.750 --> 1:22:35.560
Matty?

1:22:35.620 --> 1:22:37.990
Hey, kiddo.

1:22:40.820 --> 1:22:43.050
Hey, Matty!

1:23:39.050 --> 1:23:42.090
Matty?

1:23:42.150 --> 1:23:44.180
M-Matty, it's Mommy.

1:23:46.590 --> 1:23:48.660
[ Gasps, Groans ]

1:24:05.470 --> 1:24:09.370
[ Mangold ]
Mr. Lehman, you're gonna
have to learn to relax, son.

1:24:09.450 --> 1:24:12.820
What have you got
your panties in such
a twist about, anyhow?

1:24:14.480 --> 1:24:16.450
[ Sighs ]
You ever arrest anybody...

1:24:16.520 --> 1:24:20.190
you thought
was innocent, Mangold?
Nope.

1:24:21.920 --> 1:24:24.260
[ Beeping ]
[ Sighs ]

1:24:24.330 --> 1:24:27.400
'Course there's
no information
on Jonathan Devereaux...

1:24:27.460 --> 1:24:29.530
that's over
three years old.

1:24:29.600 --> 1:24:32.570
Three years ago
the guy didn't exist.
So he changed his name.

1:24:32.640 --> 1:24:34.640
Lots of folks
change their names, Lehman.

1:24:34.700 --> 1:24:36.630
That don't make 'em
criminals.
Yeah, but I'm betting...

1:24:36.710 --> 1:24:39.150
he changed it from Simon Ryder,
and before that, Nick Parsons.

1:24:39.210 --> 1:24:42.120
But you can't prove it.
No.

1:24:42.180 --> 1:24:44.290
** [ Playing
"Red River Valley,"
Dixieland Style ]

1:25:07.200 --> 1:25:09.200
[ Chatting Indistinctly ]

1:25:10.370 --> 1:25:12.700
Hey!
Is that long distance?

1:25:12.780 --> 1:25:15.020
Bill me.

1:25:15.080 --> 1:25:17.550
Lucy, hi.
This is Travis. Listen.

1:25:17.610 --> 1:25:20.510
I want you to get the D.M.V.
to fax me a Washington
driver's license...

1:25:20.580 --> 1:25:22.580
photograph of one
Nicholas Parsons.

1:25:22.650 --> 1:25:24.650
I'm at the New Orleans
Police Department.

1:25:24.720 --> 1:25:26.620
Travis, you better talk
to Mr. Carruthers.
Travis!

1:25:26.690 --> 1:25:30.600
His colon is twisted
in a knot.
Give me that.

1:25:30.660 --> 1:25:32.830
I've had to cover
your office for you, Travis.

1:25:32.900 --> 1:25:34.970
Where the hell
are you?
Listen to me, Karl.

1:25:35.030 --> 1:25:37.090
I think maybe
this Parsons woman
has been telling the truth.

1:25:37.170 --> 1:25:39.070
You're not
a law professor
anymore, Travis.

1:25:39.130 --> 1:25:40.960
You're barely even
a parole officer.

1:25:41.040 --> 1:25:44.180
So stop playing
Mission Impossible and--
All I need...

1:25:44.240 --> 1:25:46.940
is a D.M.V.
driver's license photograph
of Nicolas Parsons.

1:25:47.010 --> 1:25:49.080
You get back here today...

1:25:49.140 --> 1:25:51.780
because tomorrow,
you're going in front
of the Commission.

1:25:51.850 --> 1:25:55.160
Karl, I know I'm right.

1:25:55.220 --> 1:25:57.430
You give me a chance, okay?

1:25:57.490 --> 1:25:59.460
Now, I'm asking you politely.

1:25:59.520 --> 1:26:01.890
You send me
the goddamn picture!

1:26:05.490 --> 1:26:08.830
[ Libby Groans,
Flicks Cigarette Lighter ]

1:26:10.300 --> 1:26:12.370
[ Sniffs ]

1:26:17.640 --> 1:26:19.570
[ Gasps ]

1:26:19.640 --> 1:26:21.510
[ Panting ]

1:26:26.820 --> 1:26:28.660
[ Whimpering ]

1:26:39.530 --> 1:26:41.540
[ Continues Whimpering ]

1:26:52.810 --> 1:26:54.680
[ Moans ]

1:26:58.350 --> 1:27:00.390
[ Pounding, Moaning ]

1:28:00.010 --> 1:28:02.020
[ Gunshot ]

1:28:13.790 --> 1:28:16.660
[ Groans ]

1:28:29.970 --> 1:28:31.970
Hey!

1:28:32.040 --> 1:28:34.910
[ Pounding ]
Hey!

1:28:43.020 --> 1:28:44.890
[ Humming ]

1:28:51.990 --> 1:28:55.460
It's not him.
See, Lehman, the thing is,
every now and again,

1:28:55.530 --> 1:28:57.330
we all want to believe
in something,

1:28:57.400 --> 1:29:00.460
but we just keep forgetting
that 99.9 percent
of the time,

1:29:00.540 --> 1:29:02.810
life just flat
don't work out.

1:29:02.870 --> 1:29:04.900
I hadn't thought
of that, Mangold.

1:29:04.970 --> 1:29:08.370
- Thanks.
I feel a lot better now.
- Anytime, Hoss. Anytime.

1:29:18.750 --> 1:29:21.550
Hold it.
Hold it right here.

1:29:49.380 --> 1:29:51.480
It's over, Libby.

1:29:51.550 --> 1:29:54.720
[ Sobbing ]
Oh, Travis.

1:30:22.820 --> 1:30:24.690
Messages.

1:30:25.950 --> 1:30:28.350
Thank you.

1:30:28.420 --> 1:30:31.590
Mr. Devereaux?
Mr. Lehman.

1:30:31.660 --> 1:30:33.560
I'm sorry.
This is really not
a good time.

1:30:33.630 --> 1:30:35.770
I understand.

1:30:35.830 --> 1:30:38.230
A lot of people
feel that way about me.
But I have good news.

1:30:38.300 --> 1:30:42.800
- Mm-hmm?
- Won't take long.

1:30:46.270 --> 1:30:49.570
Well?
Well...

1:30:49.650 --> 1:30:52.720
turns out I owe you
an apology, Mr. Devereaux.

1:30:54.180 --> 1:30:56.610
After our last conversation
I started thinking...

1:30:56.690 --> 1:31:00.230
maybe that Parsons woman
is telling the truth about
who you used to be.

1:31:00.290 --> 1:31:04.770
[ Chuckles ]
So I asked the Washington State
Department of Motor Vehicles...

1:31:04.830 --> 1:31:09.670
to send me a driver's license
photograph of Nicholas Parsons.

1:31:10.900 --> 1:31:13.740
- And?
- And this is what came up.

1:31:18.440 --> 1:31:21.070
[ Laughing ]

1:31:23.250 --> 1:31:25.120
Well--

1:31:26.880 --> 1:31:29.210
We all make mistakes.
There's no harm done.

1:31:29.280 --> 1:31:32.250
Then I thought about it
some more, and it occurred
to me what a common name...

1:31:32.320 --> 1:31:34.320
Nicolas Parsons is.

1:31:34.390 --> 1:31:36.500
You know, it turns out
there were six.

1:31:36.560 --> 1:31:38.530
And this...

1:31:38.590 --> 1:31:41.120
was number three.

1:31:44.170 --> 1:31:46.270
I never liked that picture.

1:31:49.340 --> 1:31:52.180
So, Mr. Lehman,
you came here
to make a deal--

1:31:52.240 --> 1:31:54.400
otherwise, I guess
you would have gone
straight to the police.

1:31:54.480 --> 1:31:58.120
So, question is,
what's your price?
A million dollars.

1:31:59.310 --> 1:32:02.450
[ Laughs ]
It's a nice round figure,
right?

1:32:02.520 --> 1:32:04.590
Uh--

1:32:07.120 --> 1:32:10.120
All right. But you're
gonna have to give me
a couple of days.

1:32:10.190 --> 1:32:13.160
No way.
One million dollars,
right now.

1:32:13.230 --> 1:32:17.040
Mr. Lehman,
it's 9:00 at night.
I can't just--

1:32:17.100 --> 1:32:19.140
[ Snaps Fingers ]

1:32:20.970 --> 1:32:23.810
Wait a minute.
Wait a minute. Wait.

1:32:24.840 --> 1:32:27.570
I have $100,000
in the safe here.

1:32:27.640 --> 1:32:30.540
And you can have that now.

1:32:30.610 --> 1:32:32.610
I'll get you the rest
tomorrow.

1:32:33.620 --> 1:32:35.690
You got a deal.

1:32:38.020 --> 1:32:40.980
We do have one other problem,
and that's Mrs. Parsons.

1:32:41.060 --> 1:32:43.730
She could still make
a lot of trouble for us,
even from prison,

1:32:43.790 --> 1:32:46.590
- and I really don't need that.
- I think I've solved
that problem.

1:32:46.660 --> 1:32:50.060
- What do you mean?
- Let's just say the problem
has been buried.

1:32:50.130 --> 1:32:53.660
- Really?
- She's gone, I promise you.

1:33:04.210 --> 1:33:06.380
You're not very good
at keeping promises, Nick.

1:33:06.450 --> 1:33:09.160
You gonna do something?

1:33:09.220 --> 1:33:11.120
What are you
talking to me for?
She's the one with the gun.

1:33:19.700 --> 1:33:22.700
They're tough
in Louisiana, Libby.

1:33:22.770 --> 1:33:25.270
You shoot me,
they'll give you
the gas chamber.

1:33:25.330 --> 1:33:27.430
No, they won't.

1:33:27.500 --> 1:33:30.600
It's called double jeopardy.
I learned a few things
in prison, Nick.

1:33:30.670 --> 1:33:33.700
I could shoot you
in the middle of Mardi Gras
and they can't touch me.

1:33:33.780 --> 1:33:36.720
As an ex-law professor,
I can assure you
she is right.

1:33:40.820 --> 1:33:43.020
Where's my son?

1:33:44.920 --> 1:33:47.720
In St. Albans School
in Georgia, all right?

1:33:49.320 --> 1:33:51.690
You have your son back.
You got what you want.

1:34:02.170 --> 1:34:05.000
I haven't felt that good
in six years.

1:34:07.480 --> 1:34:09.620
I don't want
to kill you, Nick.

1:34:09.680 --> 1:34:11.690
I just want you to suffer
like I suffered.

1:34:11.750 --> 1:34:14.390
What she means, Nick,
is, you're going
to prison--

1:34:14.450 --> 1:34:16.760
for murder.

1:34:16.820 --> 1:34:19.130
- Who did I
supposedly murder?
- Me.

1:34:23.090 --> 1:34:25.960
All you've got
is an old fax photo.
Which supplies the motive.

1:34:26.030 --> 1:34:28.400
Your wife, whom you had framed,
tracks you down,

1:34:28.460 --> 1:34:31.260
and to keep her
from exposing you,
you kill her.

1:34:31.330 --> 1:34:34.030
- You won't get away with it.
- [ Tape Rewinding ]

1:34:34.100 --> 1:34:36.030
[ Nick's Voice ]
Well, I think I've
solved that problem.

1:34:36.100 --> 1:34:38.740
- [ Travis ] What do you mean?
- [ Nick ] Let's just say
the problem has been buried.

1:34:38.810 --> 1:34:41.720
- [ Travis ] Really?
- [ Nick ] She's gone,
I promise you.

1:34:41.780 --> 1:34:43.880
[ Click ]

1:34:43.950 --> 1:34:46.690
Taped confessions
are very persuasive
in court, Nick,

1:34:46.750 --> 1:34:48.620
and of course
there is...

1:34:48.680 --> 1:34:51.850
the physical evidence
that we're gonna put
in the trunk of your car.

1:34:51.920 --> 1:34:54.790
A shovel, hair, my fingerprints,
a little blood.

1:34:54.860 --> 1:34:57.800
- Don't forget the gasoline.
- It'll look like you burned
and buried my body,

1:34:57.860 --> 1:35:01.020
just like you say
on the tape.

1:35:01.100 --> 1:35:04.370
The prosecution rests.
You better get out of here.

1:35:04.430 --> 1:35:06.300
Nobody wants a dead woman
walking around when
the police...

1:35:06.370 --> 1:35:09.840
are trying to arrest a guy
for her murder.

1:35:09.910 --> 1:35:12.280
Wait a minute.
I'll take that gun.

1:35:13.410 --> 1:35:15.120
[ Screams ]

1:35:21.250 --> 1:35:23.790
[ Groans ]

1:35:53.280 --> 1:35:55.510
[ Groaning ]

1:36:03.490 --> 1:36:05.320
[ Gunshot ]

1:36:32.050 --> 1:36:34.480
Well, Lehman,
you gonna live?

1:36:37.230 --> 1:36:39.270
[ Mangold Laughing ]
I doubt it.

1:36:39.330 --> 1:36:41.870
Ms. Parsons, since you are
still legally his wife,

1:36:41.930 --> 1:36:45.260
I expect you just
inherited yourself
a right fine little hotel here.

1:36:45.330 --> 1:36:48.130
Not interested.

1:36:48.200 --> 1:36:49.570
[ Groans ]

1:36:55.680 --> 1:36:57.580
I guess I'm gonna
take off now.

1:36:57.650 --> 1:37:02.890
No. No, you're not.
You're a parole violator.
You're in my c-custody.

1:37:02.950 --> 1:37:06.220
You're going with me
to Seattle,

1:37:06.290 --> 1:37:09.900
where I will demand
a full pardon and a parade...

1:37:09.960 --> 1:37:12.270
and a little pink poodle...

1:37:13.400 --> 1:37:15.270
on a key chain.

1:37:15.330 --> 1:37:17.190
[ Laughing ]

1:37:26.440 --> 1:37:28.410
[ Boys Shouting ]
Come on, Ryan,
pass it!

1:37:30.750 --> 1:37:32.590
[ Whistle Blows ]

1:37:43.830 --> 1:37:47.600
What are you waiting for?
Go on.

1:37:50.200 --> 1:37:54.810
I don't know if I've
ever been so scared
in my whole life.

1:37:54.870 --> 1:37:57.950
I think a big part of me
never thought I'd
really find him.

1:38:00.710 --> 1:38:03.650
What if he doesn't
recognize me?

1:38:03.710 --> 1:38:06.010
I mean, maybe after
all this time--
Damn, woman!

1:38:06.080 --> 1:38:09.610
Because of you, I have lost
a perfectly good used car,
and a not-so-good job.

1:38:09.680 --> 1:38:14.450
If you don't go to this kid
right now, I'm gonna have you
arrested for stupidity.

1:38:14.520 --> 1:38:16.390
Go on.

1:38:20.860 --> 1:38:22.930
Thanks, Lehman.

1:38:23.870 --> 1:38:25.940
You saved my life.

1:38:29.900 --> 1:38:32.240
You saved mine too.

1:38:45.290 --> 1:38:48.730
Coach Matthews.
How you doing?
Nice to meet you.

1:38:48.790 --> 1:38:51.220
It'll be halftime soon.

1:39:06.410 --> 1:39:09.320
[ Whistle Blows ]
[ Matthews ]
Halftime!

1:39:09.380 --> 1:39:11.480
Matty.

1:39:12.450 --> 1:39:14.420
Matty.

1:39:28.630 --> 1:39:31.330
Hi.

1:39:34.200 --> 1:39:36.230
Do you know who I am?

1:39:38.870 --> 1:39:40.670
They told me
you were dead.

1:39:43.510 --> 1:39:45.340
No, sweetheart.

1:39:59.090 --> 1:40:01.160
[ Chuckling ]
